[1] Thailand: smuggled vaccines
Date: Mon 19 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Thai National News Bureau via VNA, 18 Jul 2004 [edited]
<http://www.vnagency.com.vn/newsa.asp?LANGUAGE_ID=2&CATEGORY_ID=33&NEWS_ID=109355>

More Thai provinces confirm bird flu outbreaks
-----------------------------------------------
Bird flu was suspected of spreading to over 8 provinces, and confirmed in
more than 10 provinces, in Thailand, according to the Thai Deputy Prime
Minister, Chaturon Chaisaeng, who said that the Cabinet would meet on
Monday [19 Jul 2004] to decide whether to penalize farms, that violate the
ban on the use of vaccines, by closing them.
Thailand Food and Drugs Agency (FDA) has not approved the use of bird-flu
vaccines, because scientific research has yet to determine whether
consuming vaccinated chickens would pose a health risk to humans.
Chaturon has assigned Yukol Limlaethong, director-general of Livestock
Development, to arrange strict measures to prevent bird flu from spreading
any further. The movement of farming equipment will be prohibited, and
farmers will be required to buy chickens only from closed-system production
facilities. Yukol said vaccination would be a last resort.
Prime Minister Thaksin Shinawatra said bird flu had broken out again,
because officials had failed to completely wipe it out earlier this year
[2004].
In Chiang Saen district, in Chiang Rai province, police have arrested a man
with 200 bottles of suspected bird-flu vaccine. He confessed to smuggling
the drug in to sell in Bangkok.
