[2] Thailand: considering vaccination
Date: Mon 19 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Nation, 19 Jul 2004 [edited]
<http://www.nationmultimedia.com/page.news.php3?clid=2&id=117519&usrsess=1>

New panel to tackle bird flu
----------------------------
The government will set up a national-level committee for combating avian
influenza, and, give it 2 months to decide whether to introduce bird-flu
vaccination in critical areas, Agriculture Minister Somsak Thepsuthin said
yesterday [Sun 18 Jul 2004].
The government is looking for a permanent solution to the disease that has
affected the country's poultry industry since early this year [2004].
However, inoculation is a subject of heated debate, because some vaccinated
fowl could carry the disease without showing symptoms, possibly putting
humans at risk in the long run.
Somsak announced the plan to experiment with the vaccine yesterday [Sun 18
Jul 2004] after a meeting with relevant agencies that was called in the
wake of fresh outbreaks of bird-flu. He said the national-level committee
on bird-flu would be assigned to research, extensively, ways to contain and
prevent outbreaks of the disease.
Somsak said the committee would be comprised of experts from the Veterinary
Council of Thailand, the Public Health Ministry, and various universities.
"The committee should have all the information ready within 2 months,
including the vaccine issue," he said.
After the research, the bird-flu vaccine should be experimented with in
some areas, Somsak said, adding that the vaccine would remain banned
outside the trial areas. "We have to move cautiously, because the disease
could spread unnoticed and pass on to humans," warned Dr. Supamit
Chunsuttiwat, a doctor from the Disease Control Division.
Dr. Wantanee Palprawit, of the Veterinary Council, explained that bird-flu
vaccine was just part of the plan to contain the disease permanently. She
said each country had different conditions, and thus, the fact that
Indonesia and China could use the vaccine did not guarantee that Thailand
could use it too. [According to the Bangkok Post, cited by the Viet Nam
News Agency on 18 Jul 2004, Thailand plans to invite a group of Chinese
experts working in infectious diseases to help conduct the experiment on
the H5N1 virus strain of bird flu. - Mod.AS].
Dr. Pirophan Puttawattana, chief virologist at Mahidol University, said the
bird-flu strain found in Thailand was H5N1, with minimal mutation, and
could not yet be passed between humans. "It's only a bit different from the
H5N1 strain that was 1st found in Hong Kong 7 years ago," said Dr. Yong
Puwan, from Chulalongkorn University's Faculty of Medicine.
Livestock Development Department director-general Yukol Limlamthong said
the fresh outbreak of bird-flu remained restricted to small areas in
13 provinces. He said his department planned to propose a zoning plan for
fowl control. "If we enforce the zoning, we will be able to know more about
the local problems in each zone, and, will be able to react more swiftly,
and efficiently, in case any problem arises," he said.
[Byline: Sirinart Sirisunthorn]
