[3] Thailand, China, Viet Nam, H5N1
Date: Mon 19 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters via Daily Times - Pakistan, 19 Jul 2004 [edited]
<http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=story_19-7-2004_pg6_14>

Bird flu calm in Thailand and China
-----------------------------------
Thailand's fresh outbreak of bird flu was spreading Friday [16 Jul 2004],
but officials said the deadly virus, which ravaged Asian fowl flocks early
in 2004, was under control in Viet Nam and China.
Bird flu has now spread to 15 of Thailand's 76 provinces since the 1st
recurrence just over a week ago [2nd week July 2004].
Officials said they were also awaiting laboratory tests on suspected cases
of the H5N1 virus, which killed 16 Vietnamese, and 8 Thais, who came in
close contact with infected fowl earlier in 2004, in 8 districts of
Bangkok. The fresh outbreak, in what was the world's 4th biggest chicken
exporter before the earlier epidemic, has devastated the Thai industry and
hit the stock market, which fell almost one percent on Thu 15 Jul 2004.
There have been no reports of anyone in China, Viet Nam, or Thailand
falling ill from bird flu in the latest outbreaks, officials in the 3
countries said. But, the government has put Thailand on high alert,
ordering officials to rush anyone to the hospital showing any symptoms that
resemble those of bird flu.
Officials in China and Viet Nam said their outbreaks had been contained,
and no new cases had been reported. "The virus is not spreading. There have
not been any new cases," Bui Quang Anh, head of the Agriculture Ministry's
animal health department in Hanoi, told Reuters.
"We are cooperating closely with OIE to evaluate the situation," he added,
referring to the Paris-based World Organization for Animal Health.
Viet Nam has confirmed outbreaks of bird flu in 7 provinces, and, has
culled 10 000 poultry, mostly ducks, to prevent the virus from spreading.
Thailand has culled more than 40 000 poultry in the latest outbreaks so
far, a figure dwarfed by the 60 million it slaughtered earlier in 2004.
In China, officials said 28 000 chickens had been culled, and 190 000
vaccinated, to contain the H5N1 outbreak. China would release the last
group of 114 people, who came into contact with chickens at the site of an
outbreak, and, were under clinical observation, in the next few days, the
officials said.
"China has stepped up inspection of border trade between the southern
region of Guangxi and Viet Nam, after poultry samples from the south of
Viet Nam were found infected with bird flu," China's quarantine bureau said
on its web-site:
.
Officials in Thailand and China have blamed wild birds -- especially
waterfowl, highly suspected of causing the main outbreak early in 2004 --
for the new cases. But, the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO), the
United Nations food body, said poor hygienic practices were to blame.
"Killing wild birds will not help to prevent, or control, avian influenza
outbreaks," said Juan Lubroth of the FAO animal health service. "To date,
there is no scientific evidence that wildlife is the major factor in the
resurgence of the disease in the region."
Poor hygienic practices in production, processing, and marketing of
poultry, contaminated products, and, individuals not following recommended
control measures were probably to blame, he said.
